UL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":35656,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1435681468,"comment_id":58425,"body":"@mgkrebbs Yes I checked that but I did not find much info on what petrichor really is. Moreover the wiki article does not have much info."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1453096254,"creation_date":1435649448,"body":"<p>That molecule is called <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1058374/\">Geosmin<\/a>. It is mainly produced <sup>1<\/sup> by <em>Actinomycetes<\/em> such as <em>Streptomyces<\/em> which are filamentous bacteria that live in soil. Other organisms also produce geosmin:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24289950\">Cyanobacteria<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/3761199\">Certain fungi<\/a><\/li>\n<li>An amoeba called <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1550-7408.1991.tb04798.x\"><em>Vanella<\/em><\/a><\/li>\n<li>A <a href=\"http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/40005331488/en/\">liverwort<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>It is an intracellular metabolite and cell damage is the primary reason attributed to its release. However <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24289950\">oxidant exposure<\/a> and <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.2166/wpt.2010.049\">transmembrane pressure<\/a> also causes geosmin release in cyanobacteria. It seems that the release is triggered by some kind of stress. <\/p>\n\n<p>I am not quite sure about their advantage to the host species.<\/p>\n\n<p><hr>\n<sup>1<\/sup> <em>or perhaps the most well-studied in<\/em><\/p>\n","answer_id":35656,"question_id":35654,"up_vote_count":33,"last_edit_date":1453096254}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/35654/what-is-it-that-creates-that-wonderful-smell-after-a-fresh-rain","last_activity_date":1453096254,"creation_date":1435648594,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is it that creates that wonderful smell after a fresh rain?","body":"<p>I've heard that the wonderful smell of a fresh rain is actually chemicals  released from the trees and grass and other plants.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What is the process that allows these chemicals to be released?<\/li>\n<li>What are the chemicals that create that smell?<\/li>\n<li>How is it advantageous for the plant to release the chemicals rather than hold onto them?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":35654,"tags":["botany","plant-physiology"],"score":33,"accepted_answer_id":35656,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3062,"up_vote_count":34,"last_edit_date":1435724786},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ORKi0.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17423,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17423/amphibient","reputation":154,"display_name":"amphibient"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":2,"post_id":42422,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453059815,"comment_id":72894,"body":"You should accurately define what you mean by <code>any way similar to human cooking<\/code>. For the moment it is unclear whether you example from episode of Life would be a good answer or not. Maybe you are interested in the use of heat in order to pre-digesting food before consumption."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ORKi0.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17423,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17423/amphibient","reputation":154,"disp