ave 46 chromosmes not 23) and after you duplicate the number you will have in G2 phase a bigger cell nucleus with 92 chromosmes not 46. And in mitosis each daughter cell will have 46 chroosmes."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/oygjk.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21242,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21242/lstbl","reputation":16,"display_name":"lstbl"},"score":0,"post_id":42408,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/df4dac098bcaede293096e7b3c6832c3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21216,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21216/vladimir","reputation":30,"display_name":"Vladimir"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452984701,"comment_id":72857,"body":"yes, minus some semantic issues, I think you have got it. I doubt you&#39;ll ever find someone agreeing that you &quot;have 92 chromosomes&quot;. You merely have 2 copies of 46 unique chromosomes. BTW, if this answer is satisfactory, please accept my answer by clicking the checkmark next to my post"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":42408,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452997000,"comment_id":72863,"body":"Liver cells can be polyploid..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/df4dac098bcaede293096e7b3c6832c3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21216,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21216/vladimir","reputation":30,"display_name":"Vladimir"},"score":0,"post_id":42408,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"edited":false,"creation_