tivity_date":1452977343,"creation_date":1452977343,"body":"<p>Humans have 46 chromosomes, 23 come from the mother and 23 come from the father. I think The easiest way to remember this is to think of the sex chromosomes--if you are male, you have one X chromosome from your mother and one Y chromosome from your father. During S-phase, the cell will make another copy of the X chromosome and the Y chromosome, so you will (technically) have 4 sex chromosomes in the cell before it divides, although you only have 2 UNIQUE sex chromosomes. After division, each daughter cell will have 2 sex chromosomes (one X and one Y). The same holds for all the other chromosomes.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, to answer your question, yes, in G2 phase, you have double the amount of chromosomes in your cell (46*2 = 92), but you only have 46 UNIQUE chromosomes in your cell. <\/p>\n","answer_id":42408,"question_id":42406,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42406/do-human-somatic-cells-have-46-chromosomes-all-the-time","last_activity_date":1452977343,"creation_date":1452974726,"answer_count":1,"title":"Do human somatic cells have 46 chromosomes all the time?","body":"<p>As far as I know, a human somatic cell has the cell cycle: <\/p>\n\n<p>Interphase and Replication (mitosis). In interphase the cell has 2 growth phases (G1 + G2) and a synthesis one (S phase being in between G1 and G2). After G2 ends, the cell will start entering mitosis.<\/p>\n\n<p>Until the S phase, the cell has only 23 chromosomes right? And only after the DNA has duplicated the number of chromosomes doubles (to 46). <\/p>\n\n<p>Please correct me if I am wrong? And will the cell in the G0 phase (after duplication and before G1) have 23 or 46 chromosomes? <\/p>\n","question_id":42406,"tags":["human-biology","cell-biology","mitosis","cell-division","cell-cycle"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":42408,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":142,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1452976480},{"owner