to be higher."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":37241,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/o6n5C.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1884,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1884/nbubis","reputation":128,"display_name":"nbubis"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1440666916,"comment_id":62474,"body":"@nbubis thanks for that. I corrected my answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a6c80e006fdcbd1801ecb109c27190fd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17537,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17537/kai","reputation":101,"display_name":"Kai"},"score":0,"post_id":37241,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440693743,"comment_id":62503,"body":"I would expect all animals, and possibly all living things, to emit infrared as metabolic reactions tend to be exothermic, even if the animal is ectothermic.  The question is that if the difference between the animal and its environment is enough for you to be able to actually detect it."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1440679557,"creation_date":1440645213,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer<\/strong><br>\nBirds emit infrared.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><br>\nObjects with a temperature higher than the background emit detectable <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infrared\">infrared<\/a> (IR). Endothermic (warmblooded) animals keep their body temperatures at around 37<sup>o<\/sup>C and given the relatively cool temperatures at the earth's surface, endotherms generally emit more IR than the background. <a href=\"http://www.britannica.com/science/endotherm\">Endothermic animals<\/a> include the mammals and birds, but also some fish. <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/gOskb.jpg\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/gOskb.jpg\" alt=\"![![hiummingbird IR\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Infrared image of a hummingbird. Source: <a href=\"http://blog.nature.org/science/2014/11/19/infrared-technology-conservation-wildlife-innovative-video/\">Nature Conservancy<\/a>.<\/sup><\/p>\n\n<p>Note that <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinosaur\">dinosaurs<\/a> were probably not ectothermic (coldblooded), but they are believed to have been <em>mesotheroms<\/em>, that is somewhere <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/news/dinosaurs-neither-warm-blooded-nor-cold-blooded-1.15399\">in-between ecto- and endothermic<\/a> <a href=\"http://www.sciencemag.org/content/344/6189/1268\">(Grady <em>et al<\/em>., 2014)<\/a>.     <\/p>\n\n<p>Also note your IR recordings will benefit from lower temperatures and reduced light-pollution from the sun, hence your recordings will be better at night than during daytime.<\/p>\n\n<p><sup><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.sciencemag.org/content/344/6189/1268\">Grady <em>et al<\/em>., <em>Science<\/em> (2014); <strong>344<\/strong>(6189): 1268-72<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n","answer_id":37241,"question_id":37240,"up_vote_count":16,"last_edit_date":1440679557},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/oNTlN.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17526,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17526/zhro","reputation":131,"display_name":"Zhro"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b62f68f2f334d828423b8706fc88c56e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16433,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16433/r-m","reputation":655,"display_name":"R.M."},"score":0,"post_id":37244,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440688142,"comment_id":62497,"body":"Minor nit - dinosaurs are typically not construed broadly enough to encompass the ancestors of any modern non-avian reptiles. The closest modern reptile to the dinosaurs (and birds) are believed to be the <i>crocodilians<\/i>, but the non-dinosaur pterosaurs branch between crocodillians and dinosaurs/birds on the evolutionary tree, meaning crocodiles - or any other reptile - aren&#39;t descended from anything which would count as a true &quot;dinosaur&quot; to a modern paleontologist."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hvS4q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17117,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17117/jd%c5%82ugosz","reputation":153,"display_name":"JDługosz"},"score":0,"post_id":37244,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440693850,"comment_id":62504,"body":"In current technical usage by people who study these things, birds <i>are<\/i> dinosaurs. Classics usage now becomes &quot;non-avien dinosaurs&quot;.  Reptiles are not dinosaurs.  Reptiles are not a mono-clade and don&#39;t follow &quot;always will be&quot; rule."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1440656403,"creation_date":1440656403,"body":"<p>Dinosaurs is a very broad term which includes both the ancestors of birds as well as modern reptiles. But that analogy stretches as far to say that a bird is a modern dinosaur and a reptile is a modern dinosaur but a bird is not a reptile. Both of their ancestors lived during the cretaceous period and tend to get lumped together.<\/p>\n\n<p>Another analogy would be that dolphins, bats, and humans are all modern-day mammals. But a dolphin does not fly and humans do not live underwater, etc.<\/p>\n\n<p>Modern-day birds descended from a group of dinosaurs called theropods which were warm-blooded dinosaurs.<\/p>\n\n<p>See here for more information:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2010/11/23/3073903.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2010/11/23/3073903.htm<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>To be specific to your question, if it is an endotherm then it will emit some level of infrared radiation, as this is their primary means of avoiding overheating.<\/p>\n\n<p>Interestingly, some birds are actually warmer than humans at 102-112F:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://animals.mom.me/signs-parakeet-cockatiel-birds-cold-8448.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://animals.mom.me/signs-parakeet-cockatiel-birds-cold-8448.html<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":37244,"question_id":37240,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37240/do-birds-emit-infra-red-radiation","last_activity_date":1452940924,"creation_date":1440643680,"answer_count":2,"title":"Do birds emit infra-red radiation?","body":"<p>I'm an electronics engineering student and I am going to use a sensor that detects infra-red emitted by birds that invade rice paddies. <\/p>\n\n<p>Do birds emit infra-red radiation?<\/p>\n","question_id":37240,"tags":["metabolism","ornithology","temperature","reptile"],"score":13,"accepted_answer_id":37241,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1970,"up_vote_count":13,"last_edit_date":1452940924},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-kkw9M6bfoo8/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAA0M/oHXbeS4bM0k/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":20784,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20784/shirin-riana","reputation":86,"display_name":"Shirin Riana"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"score":11,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4690b9a0df8a4c1e35c088b077942e6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6132,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6132/steve-jessop","reputation":320,"display_name":"Steve Jessop"},"score":1,"post_id":41781,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451182885,"comment_id":71111,"body":"Does it warrant stating explicitly that the foetus does not (for practical purposes relating to the 