ology.stackexchange.com/users/17367/chauxvive","reputation":88,"display_name":"chauxvive"},"score":0,"post_id":36951,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1439950340,"comment_id":61875,"body":"Unfortunately in my case it&#39;s simple experience living in a rural/wooded area :/ Occasionally we have to do cleanup."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1439926358,"creation_date":1439926358,"body":"<p>It depends on the temperature of the environment as well. In the heat of summer and in a watery environment, I can verify through unfortunate personal reference that stuff can decompose very quickly. I honestly didn't look at the image, but judging by your description it can't have been there a year. There would be nothing left. Hungry bacteria and decomposers would have left nothing but bones by then. I would say your guess is more on target.<\/p>\n","answer_id":36951,"question_id":36931,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/36931/decomposition-rate-of-a-body-in-a-wet-environment","last_activity_date":1452897664,"creation_date":1439879699,"answer_count":1,"title":"Decomposition Rate of A Body In A Wet Environment","body":"<p>I have a photo of a decomposing dog which is in a water logged environment. My peers and I are debating how long that body has been decomposing. They are saying it is at least a year old. I however think it's much more recent (1-3 months).<\/p>\n\n<p>My understanding is that when a body is put into a wet environment either partially submerged or fully it speeds up the decomposition process provided the water is not lacking oxygen such as if it was deep on the ocean floor.<\/p>\n\n<p>The carcass has its skull fully decomposed, which I think is due to the bacteria rich water having more access to surface area through the various orifices and also the skull having much less flesh than the rest of the body.<\/p>\n\n<p>The torso looks for the most part intact, and I don't see any bloating from gas buildup <em>(not sure when and how long such a feature would be present)<\/em>, and there appears to be a pink area which could be muscle. <\/p>\n\n<p>Would these features be typical of a recent death in this type of environment or am I overlooking some other important processes that could be speeding up or slowing down the decomposition?<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/8hUuJ.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>Photo<\/strong><\/a> <em>(image unboxed in case <strong>graphic<\/strong> for some viewers)<\/em><\/p>\n","question_id":36931,"tags":["bacteriology","decomposition","forensics"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"primarily opinion-based","is_answered":false,"view_count":53,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1452897664},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/174545182f803291559092ba87953eda?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16995,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16995/g-t","reputation":41,"display_name":"G_T"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/174545182f803291559092ba87953eda?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16995,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16995/g-t","reputation":41,"display_name":"G_T"},"score":0,"post_id":42357,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452852705,"comment_id":72688,"body":"Thank-you for your answer, and yes Populus trichocarpa is an interesting species. However its not quite wh