typed behaviors for building\n  foraging webs of remarkable biomechanical properties. (...) Prior molecular efforts have\n  focused on a handful of genes but have provided little\n  resolution to key questions such as the origin of the orb weavers.\n  We apply a next-generation sequencing approach to resolve spider\n  phylogeny, examining the relationships among its major lineages. (...)\n  <strong>These results imply independent origins for the two types of orb webs\n  (cribellate and ecribellate) or a much more ancestral origin of the\n  orb web with subsequent loss in the so-called RTA clade.<\/strong> <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>When comparing molecular family trees, orb weaving araeonoids and deinopoids seem to be more distantly related than thought.<\/p>\n\n<p>That discovery leaves two possible explanations for the evolution of the spider web: <strong>It either emerged much earlier than previously expected and was later abandoned by some species (most believe so). Or, web-spinning and the capacity to spin silk evolved multiple times.<\/strong> Both theories are viable, they just need to catch more spider families to prove which one fits better.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42370,"question_id":40008,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40008/evolution-of-spider-webs","last_activity_date":1452891755,"creation_date":1445988119,"answer_count":2,"title":"Evolution of spider webs?","body":"<p>Web making seems like a fairly complex behavior built from a pretty strong material.  So how exactly did it evolve? Do we have any clues about what kind of features/behaviors preceded web making and made it possible? Are there any examples of convergent evolution?<\/p>\n","question_id":40008,"tags":["evolution","zoology","ecology","arachnology"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":88,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9505b9216fdae1f6735ed821cfa7e7f8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type"