ition 520 (maximum end UTR).<\/p>\n","question_id":38852,"tags":["transcription"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":106,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XjZNQ.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19818,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19818/gordon-stanger","reputation":322,"display_name":"Gordon Stanger","accept_rate":57},"closed_date":1452901612,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":2,"post_id":42358,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452871208,"comment_id":72714,"body":"The &#39;no offspring&#39; barrier is a bit arbitrary, I&#39;m afraid. Consider pizzly/grolar bears, who are perfectly fertile. And yet grizzly bears and polar bears are considered two different species."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":42358,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452883705,"comment_id":72726,"body":"Could you please add a reference to where you read something. It helps to give a frame of reference to people trying to answer your question. An article in the Daily Herald, is different than one that you read in Popular Science is different that one you read in Nature."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":42358,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452884600,"comment_id":72728,"body":"Try reading this first, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reproductive_isolation\"