sbK.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13100,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13100/octopus","reputation":153,"display_name":"Octopus"},"score":1,"post_id":42359,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452939120,"comment_id":72785,"body":"This sounds like an interesting question, but I&#39;m not sure why your example doesn&#39;t count. Can you expand on that?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ae688844eeb8fe135820ff4bdfdc198f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5928,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5928/yisela","reputation":421,"display_name":"Yisela"},"score":17,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452865877,"creation_date":1452865877,"body":"<p>Well, the <strong><em>oldest intact DNA<\/em><\/strong> found is actually <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1472-4669.2009.00218.x/abstract\"><strong>419 million<\/strong> years old<\/a>, and it belongs to (not surprisingly) bacteria. Samples were extracted from surface-sterilized salt of different geological ages (23, 121, 419 million years of age, MYA). <\/p>\n\n<p>But as you mentioned, these are fragments. Studies on the <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/news/dna-has-a-521-year-half-life-1.11555\">half-life of DNA<\/a> suggest that even under ideal circumstances, DNA sequences older than 1.5 million years will be too short to be readable. <\/p>\n\n<p>The <strong>oldest genome<\/strong> known to date, though, is <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nature12323.html\"><strong>700,000<\/strong> years old<\/a>, and was recovered from samples from a horse leg bone. You were correct, the leg was in <strong>permafrost<\/strong>. That's a considerable jump from mastodon and polar bear fossils which were about 50,000 and 110,000 years old. <\/p>\n","answer_id":42360,"question_id":42359,"up_vote_count":17}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42359/ho