1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20761,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20761/rob","reputation":1,"display_name":"Rob"},"score":0,"post_id":42304,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452761797,"comment_id":72599,"body":"At least in case of physical or behavioural separation, we should call it different species, or am I wrong?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":0,"post_id":42304,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SKNLc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20761,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20761/rob","reputation":1,"display_name":"Rob"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452816322,"comment_id":72659,"body":"By physical separation, I mean geography. Imagine if there was a huge earthquake, and a giant crevasse suddenly appeared in the middle of a species&#39; territory. Animals on one side of the crevasse couldn&#39;t mate with animals on the other side - but they&#39;d still be the same species. A more familiar example is animals that migrate to islands. An animal living on the island of Newfoundland can&#39;t mate with a member of its own kind living in Japan."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":0,"post_id":42304,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SKNLc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20761,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20761/rob","reputation":1,"display_name":"Rob"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452816520,"comment_id":72660,"body":"Behavior i