vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452616253,"creation_date":1452616253,"body":"<p>The key here is that it is a question about <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitochondrial_DNA\">mitochondrial DNA<\/a>. mtDNA in humans is inherited <strong>maternally<\/strong> (from the mother). Both sons and daughters inherit mtDNA, but only the daughters will pass it on to the next generation.<\/p>\n\n<p>A child's mtDNA has to come from his or her mother, and all of a person's mitochondria are genetically identical. Therefore, children of an affected female will almost certainly have the abnormal trait, while children of an affected male will not.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42257,"question_id":42255,"up_vote_count":9}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42255/pedigree-analysis-problem","last_activity_date":1452710908,"creation_date":1452615369,"answer_count":1,"title":"Pedigree Analysis: Problem","body":"<p>I'm struggling to arrive at the answer to the following question, which appeared on a pre-test of mine and which I am now using to study the material we've learned. According to <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HbIHjsn5cHo\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> helpful video, I am assuming the possibilities for my question are also autosomal recessive, autosomal dominant, x-linked recessive, or x-linked dominant. I tried each approach as Mr. Douch did in the linked video, but I struggled to find a definitive answer. No matter which approach I picked, it seemed plausible that either the boy or the girl could have the trait, but it seems there's no guarantee that both the boy and the girl have to have the trait. During the pretest, I picked the first answer choice, both the boy and the girl, and got the answer correct by mere chance. But to say that the boy and girl are expected to have the trait would imply that there is a great deal of certainty that the trait will be passed on, right? <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The pedigree below shows how a physical trait ca