":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":1,"post_id":42252,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452592645,"comment_id":72446,"body":"Please see Christiaan&#39;s answer to Jen&#39;s question."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ed66edb8c0525e982031d3242804ceb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21139/reptile1234","reputation":8,"display_name":"Reptile1234"},"score":0,"post_id":42252,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452592946,"comment_id":72447,"body":"It is pretty much similar but i am still having trouble understanding why rod cells are required. As stated  Rods only mediates the perception of low-resolution gray-scale images, so couldn&#39;t the same image be provided by cone cells by only using black, white and gray."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":1,"post_id":42252,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452593329,"comment_id":72449,"body":"It is clearly mentioned in Christiaan&#39;s answer that rods are required for vision in low-light conditions."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ed66edb8c0525e982031d3242804ceb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21139/reptile1234","reputation":8,"display_name":"Reptile1234"},"score":0,"post_id":42253,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452596622,"comment_id":72450,"body":"But in night couldn&#39;t we have managed off with just using grayscale vision with the help of cone cells to view images. During night the cones don&#39;t work?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":42253,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ed66edb8c0525e982031d3242804ceb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21139/reptile1234","reputation":8,"display_name":"Reptile1234"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452597427,"comment_id":72453,"body":"our cones don&#39;t work at night."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ed66edb8c0525e982031d3242804ceb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21139/reptile1234","reputation":8,"display_name":"Reptile1234"},"score":0,"post_id":42253,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452598310,"comment_id":72455,"body":"So, as cones don&#39;t work at night, we need rods to help us with grayscale images."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":42253,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ed66edb8c0525e982031d3242804ceb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21139/reptile1234","reputation":8,"display_name":"Reptile1234"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452616563,"comment_id":72466,"body":"@Reptile1234 It&#39;s more that you need rods to help you see at night. Not having functional rods results in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retinitis_pigmentosa\" rel=\"nofollow\">nightblindness<\/a>. As you can imagine, not being able to see at night will affect one&#39;s ability to survive."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452599817,"creation_date":1452594736,"body":"<p>First off - <strong>both the rod and cone system measure light intensity<\/strong>; both sensory cells increase their responses when excited by more photons <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10850/\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Purves <em>et al<\/em>., 2001)<\/a>. Hence, your introductory sentence that rod detect luminescence and cones color is incorrect. They are both sensitive to luminescence. <\/p>\n\n<p>You are correct that rods detect gray scales, while cones perform color coding. Both systems can detect gray shades; while rods are limited to that, cones are not. Rods are very sensitive to light and in a dark-adapted state are capable of detecting a single photon. Hence, they operate under conditions of low-lighting at night and as such they mediate night (scotopic) vision. Cones are photon-hungry and need more light to operate (photopic conditions).<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Why have cones? Because color vision helps to detect and differentiate stuff.<\/li>\n<li>Why have rods? Because night vision is helpful.<\/li>\n<li>Why have both? To be successfully equipped to thrive in both light and dark environments.<\/li>\n<li>Do we need them both? No - even nocturnal hunters that don't have rods have been shown to be able to hunt at night. Not only that, these geckos have been shown to be able to detect color in starlight <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11279363\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Röll, 2000)<\/a>. Under these lighting conditions, human <em>retinae<\/em> rely on the rod system and are unable to detect color. <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><sub><strong>References<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10850/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Purves <em>et al<\/em>., <em>Neuroscience<\/em>, 2<sup>nd<\/sup> ed. Sunderland (MA): Sinauer Associates<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11279363\" rel=\"nofollow\">Röll, <em>J Neurocytol<\/em> (2000), <strong>29<\/strong>(7): 471-84<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":42253,"question_id":42252,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1452599817}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42252/why-is-it-necessary-to-have-both-cone-and-rod-cells-in-the-eye","last_activity_date":1452599817,"creation_date":1452591853,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is it necessary to have both cone and rod cells in the eye?","body":"<p>Our eyes have both cone and rod cells. Rod cells measure the intensity of light whereas cone cells identify the colour of the image formed in the eyes. So cone cells must also be able to identify white, black and grey and also their shades. \n<br><br>\nSo it wouldn't have been that much trouble to just have cone cells cells as identifying black and white would have been the same as measuring the intensity of light. Wouldn't it?<\/p>\n","question_id":42252,"tags":["vision","neurophysiology"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":42253,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":75,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1452595859},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/YMlKc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3776,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3776/satwik-pasani","reputation":2491,"display_name":"Satwik Pasani","accept_rate":68},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/YMlKc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3776,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3776/satwik-pasani","reputation":2491,"display_name":"Satwik Pasani","accept_rate":68},"score":0,"post_id":14142,"edited":false,"creation_date":1387965848,"comment_id":18572,"body":"Thank you. And great references, as <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14120/can-cancer-cells-in-the-same-person-organ-and-origin-have-different-dna/14122#14122\">usual.<\/a>"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452599091,"creation_date":1387964602,"body":"<p>I don't have an other explanation than pointing to evolution. It was obviously not a problem to evolve the way it did. One article I found (see \"<a href=\"http://www.arn.org/docs/odesign/od192/invertedretina192.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Inverted Retina: Maladaptation or Pre-adaptation?<\/a>\") called it a sign of pre-adaptation, where forms exist before they get their final function.\nAnother pretty comprehensive review can be found here: \"<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23926622\" rel=\"nofollow\">Evolution of Phototransduction, Vertebrate Photoreceptors and Retina.<\/a>\"<\/p>\n","answer_id":14142,"question_id":14130,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1452599091}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14130/the-arrangement-of-retinal-cells","last_activity_date":1452599499,"creation_date":1387905061,"answer_count":1,"title":"The arrangement of retinal cells?","body":"<p>The section of retina shows a layered arrangement of the various retinal cells. Starting from the inside (where the light strikes first) is the nerve fibre layer, ganglionic layer, amacrine cell layer, bipolar cell layer, horizontal cell layer and finally rods and cones (and that too in inverted position, i.e. the actual receptor portions are farther inwards).  <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><strong>Why is this stratification inverted?<\/strong> If the receptors would have been the innermost cells, they could have received the maximum\n  quantity of unaltered light. Does this \"inverted\" arrangement, i.e.\n  arrangement with the receptor cell behind a screen of several other\n  layers not hinder the process of photoreception by blocking a lot of\n  incident light and hence the formed image? <strong>What is, if any,\n  advantage of this reverse arrangement?<\/strong>  <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/KE7y5.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n","question_id":14130,"tags":["human-biology","vision","eyes","neurophysiology"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":14142,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":224,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1452599499},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1980ea1d7e33e2a5134f6f3e4d3177cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21136/ian","reputation":121,"display_name":"Ian"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1980ea1d7e33e2a5134f6f3e4d3177cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21136/ian","reputation":121,"display_name":"Ian"},"score":0,"post_id":42254,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452612858,"comment_id":72461,"body":"That makes me feel a bit better, although it doesn&#39;t look like a wolf spider either, because of its more uniform color. So I&#39;d be curious to know if anyone has a positive ID. Maybe Southern House Spider?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"score":1,"post_id":42254,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1980ea1d7e33e2a5134f6f3e4d3177cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21136/ian","reputation":121,"display_name":"Ian"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452664758,"comment_id":72505,"body":"@Ian Probably a huntsman, I&#39;d say, based on the eye arrangement."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1980ea1d7e33e2a5134f6f3e4d3177cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21136/ian","reputation":121,"display_name":"Ian"},"score":0,"post_id":42254,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452710894,"comment_id":72560,"body":"@augurar - Wouldn&#39;t a huntsman have crab shaped front legs? These look vertically jointed."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"score":0,"post_id":42254,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1980ea1d7e33e2a5134f6f3e4d3177cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21136/ian","reputation":121,"display_name":"Ian"},"edited":false,"cr