he molecule would most likely break a bond when the C became an N, but going from C to N requires converting a neutron to a proton by beta decay. The energetic electron ejected during beta decay might disrupt other parts of the molecule on its way out, but I don&#39;t really know, so this is a comment."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":42239,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452583282,"comment_id":72429,"body":"Also, it looks like chemistry won&#39;t take this question until it&#39;s deleted from here, so pick one."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/bS3hE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3703,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3703/inf3rno","reputation":2903,"display_name":"inf3rno","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":42239,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452583702,"comment_id":72430,"body":"@user137 I don&#39;t really know either, but I posted an educated guess. :D"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/bS3hE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3703,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3703/inf3rno","reputation":2903,"display_name":"inf3rno","accept_rate":50},"score":1,"post_id":42239,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452587098,"comment_id":72435,"body":"@user137 I think I found the solution, the decay has far more energy than the chemical bonds can withstand, so the molecule will fall apart."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e602b352a36dbdf26c803ccaaf91e0f5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9036,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9036/level-river-st","reputation":336,"display_name":"Level River St"},"score":0,"post_id":42239,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452596949,"comment_id":72451,"body":"Carbon 14 has a half life of about 6000 years. the only way to know for sure is to synthesize a bunch of radioactive glucose and leave it a few centuries to see what reaction products are formed. An issue is that regular glucose may decompose on a shorter timescale anyway."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/bS3hE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3703,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3703/inf3rno","reputation":2903,"display_name":"inf3rno","accept_rate":50},"score":1,"post_id":42239,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e602b352a36dbdf26c803ccaaf91e0f5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9036,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9036/level-river-st","reputation":336,"display_name":"Level River St"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452662652,"comment_id":72504,"body":"@steveverrill You never heard of atomic force microscopy I assume."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/bS3hE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3703,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3703/inf3rno","reputation":2903,"display_name":"inf3rno","accept_rate":50},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":42249,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452588510,"comment_id":72437,"body":"My guess is it&#39;s hard to study because even the C-14 to N transition is slow on lab scale, so getting enough decay products to do structural analysis is hard."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452587243,"creation_date":1452583426,"body":"<p>I am not experienced in the topic, and could not find any article related to these kind of reactions, but my guess is the following. During the nuclear transmutation the radiocarbon will lose an electron (beta particle), so the nitrogen product will have positive charge. After that there are 2 possible scenarios.<\/p>\n\n<p>a.) less plausible scenario<\/p>\n\n<p>The beta particle carries away the energy of the decay, so the molecule will have low energy and it will be able to rearrange.<\/p>\n\n<p>The electron shells will collapse a little bit, since the nitrogen has smaller nuclear radius. The part after that depends on which carbon we are talking about in the glucose molecule. I would guess the following rearrangements:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>${-CH2OH} \\rightarrow {-NHOH} + H^+ $<\/li>\n<li>${=CHOH} \\rightarrow {=NH} + H^+ $<\/li>\n<li>${-CHO} \\rightarrow {-NO} + H^+ $<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>It is not easier to break an N-H bond compared to the N-C and N-O bonds according to this <a href=\"http://chemwiki.ucdavis.edu/Theoretical_Chemistry/Chemical_Bonding/General_Principles_of_Chemical_Bonding/Bond_Energies\">table<\/a>, but I think what really matters here is the stability of the final product, and $H^+$ is way more stable than any $^+O*$, $^+C*$, etc. ion. <\/p>\n\n<p>b.) what really happens<\/p>\n\n<p>The beta particle carries away the energy of the decay only partially. So the nitrogen will have a lot of energy, which is more than enough to break all of the bonds. According to <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon-14\">wikipedia<\/a> the decay energy is 0.156476 MeV. Let's compare it with the bond energies:<\/p>\n\n<p>$ 0.156476 MeV = 2.50702189 \\cdot 10^{-17} kJ $<\/p>\n\n<p>${2.51 \\cdot 10^{-17} kJ} \\cdot {6 \\cdot 10^{23} \\cdot 1/mol} = 1.51 \\cdot 10^7 kJ/mol$<\/p>\n\n<p>According to our <a href=\"http://chemwiki.ucdavis.edu/Theoretical_Chemistry/Chemical_Bonding/General_Principles_of_Chemical_Bonding/Bond_Energies\">table<\/a> the covalent bonds have about a few hundred kJ/mol energy, e.g. a C-N bond has 305 kJ/mol energy. So it is very likely that the chemical bonds will break immediately after the decay and the molecule will fall apart.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42249,"question_id":42239,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1452587243}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42239/what-would-happen-if-carbon-14-was-in-a-glucose-molecule-and-decayed-into-nitrog","last_activity_date":1452587243,"creation_date":1452571227,"answer_count":1,"title":"What would happen if Carbon-14 was in a glucose molecule and decayed into Nitrogen?","body":"<p>This interested me because of Melvin Calvin's experiment with photosynthesis where he used radioactive Carbon-14. If a plant used it as a reactant to make glucose, and that Carbon-14 decayed into nitrogen, what would happen to the molecule?<\/p>\n","question_id":42239,"tags":["biochemistry"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":42249,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":141,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1535938469/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":21131,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21131/aloizio-macedo","reputation":116,"display_name":"Aloizio Macedo"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SGxqm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18860,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18860/harry-vervet","reputation":1769,"display_name":"Harry Vervet"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":0,"post_id":42240,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452572842,"comment_id":72414,"body":"This is a good, but not precisely correct answer. Bats are an exception; there have been cases of rabies in people exposed to but not bitten or even scratched by bats. The mechanism is a &quot;postulated unknown bite&quot;, but it is postulated. Petting a rabid bat most certainly constitutes an exposure and such a person <i>would<\/i> be given post-exposure prophyllaxis per CDC guidelines."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SGxqm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18860,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18860/harry-vervet","reputation":1769,"display_name":"Harry Vervet"},"score":0,"post_id":42240,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452573734,"comment_id":72416,"body":"@anongoodnurse PEP is not indicated for category I exposures, such as petting a rabid animal - even a bat. It is somewhat dependent upon the history, however. You are correct in that if a person cannot completely exclude the possibility of being bitten by the bat (e.g. they were sleeping in the same room) then they will likely receive PEP. We do err on the side of caution, so I&#39;m sure category I exposures often get PEP, but this has to be balanced against the cost and inconvenience of getting the injections."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/us