user_type":"registered","user_id":19568,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19568/joel","reputation":118,"display_name":"Joel"},"score":0,"post_id":42223,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452514617,"comment_id":72380,"body":"I&#39;m not sure what your last sentence means. The bread is absorbing the water."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3363534a62c163bf91814cd024889dd8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19568,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19568/joel","reputation":118,"display_name":"Joel"},"score":3,"post_id":42223,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452514821,"comment_id":72381,"body":"Osmosis refers specifically to the diffusion of water across a semi-permeable membrane."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452558051,"creation_date":1452558051,"body":"<p>The phenomena that you are describing, where bread, which is a porous material, similar to a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sponge_(material)\" rel=\"nofollow\">sponge<\/a>, absorbs water, is the absorption of water by <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capillary_action\" rel=\"nofollow\">capillary action<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>As @Joel mentioned, <strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osmosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">osmosis<\/a><\/strong> is specifically the flow of a fluid across a semipermeable membrane, such as the plasma membrane of a cell or dialysis tubing, that occurs in such a way as to cause a flow from an area of low concentration to an area of high concentration. This flow eventually leads to a state of equilibrium when the concentration on both sides of the membrane is the same.<\/p>\n\n<p>The wikipedia article on Osmosis gives this definition:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Osmosis is the spontaneous net movement of solvent molecules through a semi-permeable membrane into a region of higher solute concentration, in the direction that tends to equalize the solute concentrations on the two sides. It may also be used to describe a physical process in which any solvent moves across a semipermeable membrane (permeable to the solvent, but not the solute) separating two solutions of different concentrations. Osmosis can be made to do work.<br>\n  <sup>- <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osmosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia: Osmosis<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/mWYBj.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/mWYBj.jpg\" alt=\"By OpenStax College [CC BY 3.0 (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0)], via Wikimedia Commons\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>- By OpenStax College [CC BY 3.0 (<a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0)]\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0)]<\/a>, via Wikimedia Commons<\/sup><\/p>\n\n<p>The bread is not selectively permeable, and it will continue to absorb liquid until it is fully saturated. This isn't actually an equilibrium, because additional water would do nothing to change the concentration on one side of the bread or the other. If you added more water to one side of a semipermeable membrane in equilibrium, by <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Chatelier%27s_principle\" rel=\"nofollow\">Le Chatelier's principle<\/a>, you are will force the reaction (in this case, you change the concentration) to one side, then the liquid would again flow from the area of low concentration to the area of high concentration.<\/p>\n\n<p>Capillary action is the result of water flowing into the small spaces, such as the air bubble that form in bread when it bakes, in the absence of a force \"pushing\" it into those spaces, or against the force of gravity. The liquid accomplishes this through <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intermolecular_force\" rel=\"nofollow\">intermolecular forces<\/a> that cause <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adhesion\" rel=\"nofollow\">adhesion<\/a> of the molecule to the surface of the material that is absorbing it and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cohesion_(chemistry)\" rel=\"nofollow\">cohesion<\/a> of the molecules in the liquid keep them associated to one another, and as the liquid moves into the spaces, it is able to pull the other liquid molecules along into the space.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42233,"question_id":42223,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42223/why-is-the-swelling-of-bread-when-placed-in-water-not-considered-to-be-caused-by","last_activity_date":1452558548,"creation_date":1452513967,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is the swelling of bread when placed in water not considered to be caused by osmosis?","body":"<p>Why is bread swelling up when placed in water not considered to be caused by osmosis? <\/p>\n\n<p>Is there a property of water that should make it leave the bread instead of enter?<\/p>\n","question_id":42223,"tags":["chemistry","membrane-transport","osmosis"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":true,"view_count":64,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1452558548},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8bbc94977312d285045b2412257b6cb8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1195,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1195/kenorb","reputation":285,"display_name":"kenorb","accept_rate":67},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"score":12,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":31653,"edited":false,"creation_date":1429810776,"comment_id":53160,"body":"Would it be fair to say that a counter to blood not being an organ is that blood has multiple cell types? But what is key to remember is that tissues are organised structures of different tissues. Blood has very little organisation due to its fluidity."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2d50eaca20365c51634c9452835c50ab?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":14629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14629/cactuswoman","reputation":1902,"display_name":"CactusWoman","accept_rate":60},"score":1,"post_id":31653,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"edited":false,"creation_date":1429810947,"comment_id":53161,"body":"@Good Gravy I suspect that the fact that blood lacks structure is a reason why not everyone considers it to be a tissue. As far as I know, the multiple cell types themselves are not considered to be separate tissues by anyone (for instance, we don&#39;t consider blood to be composed of red blood cell tissue and white blood cell tissue), but then again this is not my area of expertise so I wouldn&#39;t be able to say for sure"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429807085,"creation_date":1429807085,"body":"<p>Blood is considered a type of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connective_tissue\">connective tissue<\/a> (sometimes). However, an organ is formed of multiple <em>different<\/em> tissues. Thus, blood is a tissue, not an organ.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31653,"question_id":31652,"up_vote_count":12},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":31654,"edited":false,"creation_date":1429885287,"comment_id":53214,"body":"Any reason for the downvote?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/dITzT.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14698,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14698/sleepses","reputation":532,"display_name":"Sleepses"},"score":0,"post_id":31654,"edited":false,"creation_date":1430925327,"comment_id":54265,"body":"Sorry for the late update. I don&#39;t think multitude of functionality is an criterion of being an organ or not. Organs like the liver also have a multitude of uses which are not necessarily related. One could also argue that the functions you listed are also a group of closely related functions (transport and dissipation)."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1429809388,"creation_date":1429809388,"body":"<p>While organs are generally considered to have a single, specified function (or perhaps a group of closely-related functions), blood (the fluid inside the vessels, not the vessels themselves) has many different functions:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>deliver $O_2$ from lungs to cells<\/li>\n<li>remove waste $CO_2$ from cells to lungs<\/li>\n<li>respond to injury by clotting<\/li>\n<li>carry multiple different types of nutrients by multiple different means (free-floating, carrier protein-associated, lipid particles, etc.)<\/li>\n<li>provide transport for the immune system, which in itself has diverse functions<\/li>\n<li>transport waste products to liver and kidneys<\/li>\n<li>move regulatory molecules around the body (hormones, chemokines, cytokines, antibodies, etc.)<\/li>\n<li>regulate heat in the body<\/li>\n<li>maintain $pH$ and $H_2O$ balance<\/li>\n<li>and probably more I haven't thought of<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>So, I don't think blood should be classified as an organ, just because of its multitude of uses. Instead, it is vital for the proper functioning of pretty much all the organs in the body, and allows for connections among them.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31654,"question_id":31652,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31652/is-blood-an-organ-according-to-biology","last_activity_date":1452555466,"creation_date":1429806762,"answer_count":2,"title":"Is blood an organ according to biology?","body":"<p>It consist approximately 7 percent of body weight.<\/p>\n\n<p>By definition organ is composed of multiple tissues. Blood is a fluid, a circulating tissue.<\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore can we call this fluid system a liquid organ? <\/p>\n","question_id":31652,"tags":["hematology","definitions","organs"],"score":9,"accepted_answer_id":31653,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":4814,"up_vote_count":9},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7ff344fb84a2fa44d7f1ca1754525a7d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":10017,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10017/grtnosed","reputation":26,"display_name":"grtnosed"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1452548221,"creation_date":1414833600,"body":"<p>Senses in general <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_adaptation\" rel=\"nofollow\">adapt<\/a> to continuous stimulation due to various processes. One such process is simply the exhaustion of the reserves of a <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Sensory+Receptor+Cells\" rel=\"nofollow\">receptor<\/a>, or secondary neuron, due to a depletion of neurotransmitters. Entering a room activates a fresh pool of chemical receptors, thereby generating a clear sense of smell. However, this dims due to adaptation. Exiting and re-entering the room after a while revives the neuronal response. More <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_adaptation\" rel=\"nofollow\">central adaptive responses<\/a> may also play a role. A comparable effect is seen in the tactile sense. For example, the awareness of wearing a ring or watch fades quickly. Changing its position revives the percept. So yes, sensory systems like olfaction and touch are more responsive to <strong>differential stimuli<\/strong>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":23636,"question_id":23634,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1452548221}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/23634/does-our-nose-detect-only-if-there-is-change-in-odor","last_activity_date":1452548221,"creation_date":1414820114,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does our nose detect only if there is change in odor?","body":"<p>If I enter a room with certain odor, I can sense the odor. However, if I stay there for some time I cannot sense it anymore. A new entrant to the room can still smell it or I have to leave the room for some time and upon returning I can sense it again. Does our nose detect only if there is change in odor? <\/p>\n","question_id":23634,"tags":["physiology","senses","olfaction","nose"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":61,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1452543460},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/zMddS.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20863,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20863/jen","reputation":369,"display_name":"Jen","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":8,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/zMddS.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20863,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20863/jen","reputation":369,"display_name":"Jen","accept_rate":100},"score":2,"post_id":42221,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452545927,"comment_id":72397,"body":"Great answer!!!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/zMddS.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20863,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20863/jen","reputation":369,"display_name":"Jen","accept_rate":100},"score":1,"post_id":42221,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452638733,"comment_id":72488,"body":"So I person who has trouble seeing at night to drive may have low rod count?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"post_id":42221,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/zMddS.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20863,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20863/jen","reputation":369,"display_name":"Jen","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452639186,"comment_id":72489,"body":"@Jen - May be, for example in retinitis pigmentosa sufferers the outer retina degenerates and with it the rods. Among the first signs is indeed night blindness.  I&#39;ll edit my answer to include this when I find the time - good point."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.im